
"Goiter":"Often depicted in Renaissance art with "da Vinci Sign", possibly as a stylized beauty ideal or reflection of high social status","As early as 1600BC, Chinese physicians were using seaweed and burnt sponge as treatment options, probably effective due to the iodine content","After salt iodization, this condition is frequently only seen in autoimmune conditions now"
"acyclovir":"Nucleosides found in the 1950s in a Caribbean sponge, Cryptotethya crypta ultimately led to the development of this drug and approval in 1981","Because this medication is activated only inside affected cells by thymidine kinase, it was the first drug to destroy viruses without harming host cells","Despite being discovered decades ago, this remains the most widely prescribed antiviral for multiple indications"
"Hyperparathyroidism","primary hyperparathyroidism","HPT":"Initially only diagnosed when severe and life threatening, the advent of new testing has led to most cases being detected in asymptomatic patients now","In advanced cases, benign lytic lesions can form often in the jaws or long bones","In the outpatient setting, this is the most common cause of hypercalcemia"
"Aortic stenosis":"Historically affecting patients in their mid-life in the mid-20th century, this is now primarily considered a disease of the elderly","Mortality rates of this are cited at 50-60% within 2 years of symptom onset but if treated, the 2 year survival rises to 90%","Initially diagnosed by X-ray, this is now frequently found on ultrasound instead"
"Rheumatic fever": "A leading cause of death during the early 20th century, this is now rare in developed countries today","Although associated with a bacterial illness, the disease is actually caused by molecular mimicry","Causing migratory joint pain and chorea, this disease can frequently cause long term damage to the heart valves"
"Glucose": "First isolated from raisins in 1747 by a German chemist, frequent monitoring of this is required for some patients","Also known as C6H12O6, the current term is derived from a greek word referring to sweet wine","Critical for creating ATP, the brain relies on this as its primary energy source"
"Appendix": "Believed to have evolved over 80 million years ago, this was described in the early 1500s in drawings by Leonardo da Vinci","Holding high concentrations of lymphoid tissue, this organ has been reported to grow as long as 10.24 inches long","Due to comparisons to a worm, this is frequently described as 'vermiform'"
"Bumetanide","bumex": "Highly bioavailable, researchers are currently studying this drug for use in neurological disorders like autism and schizophrenia","Roughly 40-60 times more potent than others in this class of medications, this medication acts on the thick ascending limb","A nasal spray formulation, Embumyst, was approved by the FDA in 2025"
"furosemide","lasix": "This medication is on the World Anti-Doping Agency's list of banned substances as it can mask the presence of other performance-enhancing drugs although still used extensively in horse racing to treat exercise-induced pulmonary hemorrhage","Available subcutaneously since 2022, this medication is used in about 14% of admitted patients","Acting specifically on the ascending limb of the loop of Henle, this medication replaced less effecive and toxic mercury derived options" 
